\setdisplaytitle{Cofinal Subdiagram}

\begin{definition}
A functor \(F : \mathcal J \to \mathcal D\) is said to be \textbf{cofinal} if
\begin{itemize}
\item For every object \(A \in \mathcal D\) there is an object \(B \in \mathcal J\) with a morphism \(f : A \to F(B)\).
\item For any two such morphisms \(f, g\), there are two more morphisms in \(\mathcal J\) such that the following commutes:
\begin{cd}
A \ar[d, "g"'] \ar[r, "f"] & F(B) \ar[d, "F(u)"] \\
F(C) \ar[r, "F(v)"'] & F(D)
\end{cd}
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

Note that "cofinal" roughly means the two things have a common (i.e. \emph{co-}) tail (i.e. \emph{final}). These two components have no relation to the usual categorical notion of duality or terminal objects.
